# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: be-cyrillic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:be-cyrillic/6] A six-sided polygon is a hexagon, one of the three regular polygons capable of tiling the plane.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] A hexagon also has 6 edges as well as 6 internal and external angles.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] 6 is the second smallest composite number.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] It is also the first number that is the sum of its proper divisors, making it the smallest perfect number.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] It is also the only perfect number that doesn't have a digital root of 1.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] 6 is the first unitary perfect number, since it is the sum of its positive proper unitary divisors, without including itself.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] Only five such numbers are known to exist.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] 6 is the largest of the four all-Harshad numbers.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] 6 is the 2nd superior highly composite number, the 2nd colossally abundant number, the 3rd triangular number, the 4th highly composite number, a pronic number, a congruent number, a harmonic divisor number, and a semiprime.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] 6 is also the first Granville number, or ${\mathcal {S}}$ -perfect number.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] A Golomb ruler of length 6 is a "perfect ruler".
[src:be-cyrillic/6] The six exponentials theorem guarantees that under certain conditions one of a set of six exponentials is transcendental.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] The smallest non-abelian group is the symmetric group $\mathrm {S_{3}}$ which has 3! = 6 elements.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] 6 the answer to the two-dimensional kissing number problem.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] In four dimensions, there are a total of six convex regular polytopes.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] The remaining **six** sporadic groups do not divide the order of the friendly giant, which are termed the ***pariahs*** (*Ly*, *O'N*, *Ru*, *J*4, *J*3, and *J*1).
[src:be-cyrillic/6] 6 is the smallest integer which is not an exponent of a prime number, making it the smallest integer greater than 1 for which there does not exist a finite field of that size.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] The SI prefix for 10006 is exa- (E), and for its reciprocal atto- (a).
[src:be-cyrillic/6] The evolution of the modern digit 6 appears to be more simple when compared with the other digits.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] The modern 6 can be traced back to the Brahmi numerals of India, which are first known from the Edicts of Ashoka c.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] It was written in one stroke like a cursive lowercase e rotated 90 degrees clockwise.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] Gradually, the upper part of the stroke (above the central squiggle) became more curved, while the lower part of the stroke (below the central squiggle) became straighter.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] The Arabs dropped the part of the stroke below the squiggle.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] From there, the European evolution to our modern 6 was very straightforward, aside from a flirtation with a glyph that looked more like an uppercase G.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] On the seven-segment displays of calculators and watches, 6 is usually written with six segments.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] Some historical calculator models use just five segments for the 6, by omitting the top horizontal bar.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] This glyph variant has not caught on; for calculators that can display results in hexadecimal, a 6 that looks like a "b" is not practical.
[src:be-cyrillic/6] Just as in most modern typefaces, in typefaces with text figures the character for the digit 6 usually has an ascender, as, for example, in .
[src:be-cyrillic/6] To disambiguate the two on objects and documents that can be inverted, the 6 has often been underlined, both in handwriting and on printed labels.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:be-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:be-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is used in the Chuvash and in both Eastern Khanty and Northern Khanty alphabets.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It appears in some Nenets dictionaries as well.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In certain orthographical varieties of Bulgarian, such as in the Primer with Various Instructions, this letter was used for the sound /ɤ/.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In modern Bulgarian, this sound is represented by the letter Ъ.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In Chuvash, ⟨ӑ⟩ represents the mid central vowel [ə], as ⟨a⟩ in word "er**a**".
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is always reduced and can occur stressed only in the first syllable of a polysyllabic word.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] The sound varies in its phonetic realization from a reduced /i/ or [ə] (like the pronunciation of ⟨a⟩ in English "sof**a**") to a labialized version of the ⟨a⟩ in English "**a**ll" (with rounded lips).
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is sometimes so reduced as to sound coalesced with the following consonant as in сӑтел *table*, /stel/.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Nineteenth century polymath Mykhailo Maksymovych used an orthography for the Ukrainian language based on etymological principles of spelling, which included the letter А̂ .
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] This letter is also used in some dialects of South Slavic languages such as Bulgarian and Serbian (e.g. гла̂ва or кра̂к).
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̂ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̂ (U+0302).
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It is used in the Khanty, Kildin Sami, Ter Sami, and Hill Mari languages.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Also, this letter was once used in the Gagauz language (which was substituted with ⟨аь⟩).
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It was used in the Bashkir language at the end of the 19th century.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It corresponds to the Cyrillic letter schwa ⟨ә⟩ in modern Bashkir.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] This letter also appears in Bulgarian and Serbian in some of its dialects.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Hill Mari and Gagauz this letter represents the near-open front unrounded vowel, /æ/.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Kildin Sami and Ter Sami this letter represents the open back unrounded vowel /a/ following a palatalized (sometimes also called "half-palatalized") velar nasal /nʲ/ or one of the alveolar stops /tʲ/ or /dʲ/.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Khanty this letter represents the near-open central vowel /ɐ/.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Some languages represent as /ja/, like in letter "Я".
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] A with diaeresis is used in some South Slavic languages, mainly in the Bulgarian and Serbian language to be used for easily shifting the accents in the above languages not only in declensions but elsewhere: брӓт or млāдä.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the Aleut (Bering dialect), Evenki, Ingush, Mansi, Nanai, Orok, Ulch, Kildin Sami, Selkup, and Chechen languages.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron also appears in the Bulgarian and Serbian languages in some dialects.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the South Slavic languages mostly in Bulgarian usually used before or after another stressed vowel: **глāвà**, **крāкà**, **овчāрè**, **ковāчè**, **юнāцѝ**, and **граждāнè**.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-macron-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̄ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̄ (U+0304).
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Хрэстоматия вейска чили збюр выписов з рожных польских ауторов".
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Грамматыка е̨зыка польскего. На кляссэ̨ I". Въ друкарни р̌а̨довэй пр̌и коммиссыи р̌а̨довэй осьвецэня публичнэго.
[src:be-cyrillic/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Lithuania - Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, Third Partition, Russian Revolution, League of Nations, Klaipėda | Britannica".
[src:be-cyrillic/be-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letters Be and Ve (В в) were both derived from the Greek letter Beta (Β β).
[src:be-cyrillic/be-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet the name of the letter Be was бѹкꙑ (*buky*/буки), meaning "letter".
[src:be-cyrillic/be-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the letter Be had no numeric value because the letter Ve inherited the Greek letter Beta's numeric value.
[src:be-cyrillic/be-cyrillic] The Russian small letter б (*be*) is similar (but not identical) in shape to the digit 6.
[src:be-cyrillic/be-cyrillic] Its lowercase form also somewhat resembles a lowercase letter B ("b"), the letter to which it corresponds in the Latin alphabet.
[src:be-cyrillic/be-cyrillic] After all, the lowercase Latin letter B ("b") developed from scribal alterations to the capital letter B ("B"), just as б did from scribal alterations to the capital letter В ("Ve").
[src:be-cyrillic/be-cyrillic] In Serbian and Macedonian the italic form is allowed to vary, but the regular should look like in other languages.
[src:be-cyrillic/be-cyrillic] The cursive form of the lowercase letter Be resembles the lowercase Greek letter Delta (δ), but they are slightly different in their upper portions.
[src:be-cyrillic/be-cyrillic] In Russian and Bulgarian, the letter Be generally represents the voiced bilabial plosive /b/, but word-finally or before a voiceless consonant, it also represents the voiceless [p].
[src:be-cyrillic/be-cyrillic] Before a palatalizing vowel, it represents /bʲ/.
[src:be-cyrillic/be-cyrillic] In Macedonian, the letter represents the sound /b/, but if it is in the final position of the word, it is pronounced as /p/, like in леб /lɛp/ ('bread').
[src:be-cyrillic/be-cyrillic] In Mari, it may represent either /b/ or the voiced bilabial fricative /β/.
[src:be-cyrillic/be-cyrillic] In Serbian, the letter represents the voiced bilabial plosive /b/, regardless of the position in the word.
